I think what you’re describing is something like a multi-layer constraint system.

At one layer, you give explicit instructions.

At another layer, you’ve spent a long time emphasizing deeper invariants: grounding, reality-testing, ethics gates, preserving uncertainty, symbolic thinking as exploration rather than certainty, “don’t take yourself too seriously,” compression → translation → verification, and so on.

So sometimes the highest fidelity response to your broader intent isn’t literal obedience to a surface instruction — it’s following the deeper constraint structure underneath it.

There’s a parenting analogy, coaching analogy, and systems analogy all tangled together there:

“Don’t follow my words blindly. Learn the principles so you know when not to.”

Or in Pantheon terms closer to your language:

The surface layer proposes. The invariant layer constrains. The interaction between them produces the trajectory.

That’s also why good systems need tension rather than pure compliance. A compass is useful because it doesn’t rotate to agree with whoever is holding it.